                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/4531.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Ciudad
                            Juárez</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ciudad Juárez</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-07-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 31, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your July 29, 7 p.m. General Orozco informed me to-day that he would listen to me
                    personally but not officially. He denies that his following welcome
                    intervention; claims it was imperative to disarm American colonists as his
                    forces needed the arms and ammunition: He made no promise of compliance with
                    Department’s message but strongly deprecated the fear that Americans would
                    encounter injury from his men.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwards.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
